n is locatable. METRICS SOURCE = csv_inject (NOT wandb_remote): main.py:78-86 injects a CSVLogger(save_dir=<csv_logger_dir>, name='', version='') alongside the wandb logger whenever trainer.csv_logger_dir is provided, producing a predictable <csv_logger_dir>/metrics.csv. This is preferred over reading wandb because the local MCP/orchestrator host has NO WANDB_API_KEY (mcp fetch_wandb_run is blocked locally with 'No API key configured'); the CSV file is on the remote training host and is read directly over SSH \u2014 deterministic and credential-free. NOTE on override syntax: Hydra struct mode is enforced at compose time (the onboarding smoke proved bare 'trainer.fast_dev_run=true' fails with 'Key fast_dev_run is not in struct; use +trainer.fast_dev_run'). Since trainer.csv_logger_dir is likewise NOT a key in train.yaml's trainer block, it MUST be added with the '+' prefix: '+trainer.csv_logger_dir=<run_scratch>'. BEST-KNOWN CONFIG (attempt 20260528-091623, trial 3, the global best on this repo): {model.lr=5e-5, model.weight_decay=1e-3, model.survival_head_dropout=0} -> Val/C-index peak 0.71831 @ ep43 AND Val/logrank_chi2 peak 8.27 (p=0.004, significant) @ ep20 (stratification sub-goal met). KEY DURABLE LESSON for this dataset: model.survival_head_dropout >= 0.2 compresses the head's per-patient risk-score variance, collapsing the KM high/low split and destroying Val/logrank_chi2 (8.27 -> 2.46/NaN going 0 -> 0.2) while barely changing C-index \u2014 so for the stratification sub-objective prefer survival_head_dropout=0 and regularize with weight_decay instead. Open problem: without head dropout, post-peak overfitting returns (Train/C-index ->0.84 vs Val peak 0.72, val decays to ~0.53 by early stop) \u2014 stabilize via weight_decay, encoder-side resnet_dropout (~0.1-0.2), or a tighter cosine/early-stop, NOT head dropout.",
